{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472320"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:56:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:56:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1238"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1238"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.02,0.86,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1238"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106991"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1238"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1238"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89455"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"676"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2206"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2489"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39630"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106991"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of progressively worsening bilateral blurry vision. She reports difficulty reading the whiteboard at school. She has worn prescription glasses since age 12 but notes she has required more frequent prescription changes over the past two years. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. Her immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Visual acuity is 6/18 in the right eye and 6/24 in the left eye, improving only slightly with pinhole testing. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pterygium","Keratitis","Keratoconus","Conjunctivitis","Acute angle closure glaucoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Ekeratoconus\u003C/strong\u003E, a non-inflammatory, progressive corneal thinning disorder that causes the cornea to bulge outward into a cone-like shape. The condition typically presents in adolescence or early adulthood with progressive myopia, irregular astigmatism, and frequent changes in glasses prescription. The slit lamp examination showing corneal thinning and protrusion as pictured is pathognomonic. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPterygium\u003C/strong\u003E is a triangular growth of fibrovascular tissue that extends from the conjunctiva onto the cornea, typically on the nasal side. It is associated with ultraviolet light exposure and presents as a fleshy growth rather than corneal thinning and protrusion, as well as more typically in older patients. Pterygium would not cause the bilateral visual changes described in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKeratitis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to inflammation of the cornea, which can be caused by infection (bacterial, viral, fungal) or non-infectious factors. It typically presents with pain, photophobia, tearing, and redness. The gradual onset of symptoms over months and the absence of inflammatory signs make keratitis unlikely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E is inflammation of the conjunctiva characterised by redness, discharge, and irritation. It does not cause corneal thinning or protrusion and would not lead to the progressive visual changes described in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute angle closure glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E presents with sudden onset of severe eye pain, headache, nausea, vomiting, and decreased vision. It is an ocular emergency that would not present with the gradual progression of symptoms over months as described in this case. Additionally, it typically affects older adults rather than adolescents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of keratoconus depends on the severity. Early cases can be managed with glasses or specialised contact lenses to reduce visual distortion. More advanced cases may require corneal collagen cross-linking to strengthen the cornea and halt progression. In severe cases with significant corneal scarring, corneal graph surgery may be necessary. This patient should be referred to an ophthalmologist for comprehensive evaluation and management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Keratoconus is a progressive corneal thinning disorder causing conical deformation and visual distortion, typically affecting adolescents and young adults.","Frequent changes in glasses prescription in adolescents with progressive visual disturbance should raise suspicion for keratoconus.","Corneal topography is the gold standard for diagnosing keratoconus, revealing the characteristic cone-shaped protrusion."],"references":["Bowling, B. (2015). Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). W B Saunders."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89455"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1238"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18414"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18414"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/69d0edc8-